=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-galbraith2012m=
athpkcbook-rsarabinenc-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-rfc8017_10-1" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#=
cite_note-rfc8017-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_encapsulation_mechanism" t=
itle=3D"Key encapsulation mechanism">public-key key encapsulation</a>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-shoup2001isoproposal_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-shoup2001isoproposal=
-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-ferguson-kohno-schneier2010cryptoengine=
ering_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RS=
A_cryptosystem#cite_note-ferguson-kohno-schneier2010cryptoengineering-15"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-rfc9690_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-rfc9690-16"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>In RSA-based cryptography, a user's <i>private key</i>=E2=80=94which=
 can be used to sign messages, or decrypt messages sent to that user=E2=80=
=94is a pair of large prime numbers chosen at random and kept secret.
A user's <i>public key</i>=E2=80=94which can be used to verify messages fro=
m the user, or encrypt messages so that only that user can decrypt them=E2=
=80=94is the product of the prime numbers.
</p><p>The security of RSA is related to the difficulty of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorization" title=3D"Factorization">factoring</=
a> the product of two large <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_=
number" title=3D"Prime number">prime numbers</a>, the "<a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factoring_problem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fact=
oring problem">factoring problem</a>". Breaking RSA encryption is known as =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_problem" title=3D"RSA prob=
lem">RSA problem</a>. Whether it is as difficult as the factoring problem i=
s an open question.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The=
re are no published methods to defeat the system if a large enough key is u=
sed.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Adi_Shamir_2009_crop.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-de=
scription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb=
/0/06/Adi_Shamir_2009_crop.jpg/250px-Adi_Shamir_2009_crop.jpg" decoding=3D"=
async" width=3D"180" height=3D"264" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wid=
th=3D"600" data-file-height=3D"879"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Adi_Shamir" title=3D"Adi Shamir">Adi Shamir</a>, co-inven=
tor of RSA (the others are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ron_Riv=
est" title=3D"Ron Rivest">Ron Rivest</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Leonard_Adleman" title=3D"Leonard Adleman">Leonard Adleman</a>)<=
/figcaption></figure>
<p>The idea of an asymmetric public-private key cryptosystem is attributed =
to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitfield_Diffie" title=3D"Whit=
field Diffie">Whitfield Diffie</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Martin_Hellman" title=3D"Martin Hellman">Martin Hellman</a>, who publi=
shed this concept in 1976. They also introduced digital signatures and atte=
mpted to apply number theory. Their formulation used a shared-secret-key cr=
eated from exponentiation of some number, modulo a prime number. However, t=
hey left open the problem of realizing a one-way function, possibly because=
 the difficulty of factoring was not well-studied at the time.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA=
_cryptosystem#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Moreover, like <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange" title=3D"Diffie=
=E2=80=93Hellman key exchange">Diffie-Hellman</a>, RSA is based on <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_exponentiation" title=3D"Modular =
exponentiation">modular exponentiation</a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ron_Rivest" title=3D"Ron Ri=
vest">Ron Rivest</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adi_Shamir" =
title=3D"Adi Shamir">Adi Shamir</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Leonard_Adleman" title=3D"Leonard Adleman">Leonard Adleman</a> at th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Techn=
ology" title=3D"Massachusetts Institute of Technology">Massachusetts Instit=
ute of Technology</a> made several attempts over the course of a year to cr=
eate a function that was hard to invert. Rivest and Shamir, as computer sci=
entists, proposed many potential functions, while Adleman, as a mathematici=
an, was responsible for finding their weaknesses. They tried many approache=
s, including "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knapsack_problem" ti=
tle=3D"Knapsack problem">knapsack</a>-based" and "permutation polynomials".=
 For a time, they thought what they wanted to achieve was impossible due to=
 contradictory requirements.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-19"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> In April 1977, they spent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pa=
ssover" title=3D"Passover">Passover</a> at the house of a student and drank=
 a good deal of wine before returning to their homes at around midnight.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Rivest, unable to sleep, =
lay on the couch with a math textbook and started thinking about their one-=
way function. He spent the rest of the night formalizing his idea, and he h=
ad much of the paper ready by daybreak. The algorithm is now known as RSA&n=
bsp;=E2=80=93  the initials of their surnames in same order as their paper.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIAM_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-SIAM-21"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clifford_Cocks" title=3D"Cl=
ifford Cocks">Clifford Cocks</a>, an English <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mathematician" title=3D"Mathematician">mathematician</a> working=
 for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom" title=3D"=
United Kingdom">British</a> intelligence agency <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Government_Communications_Headquarters" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Government Communications Headquarters">Government Communications=
 Headquarters</a> (GCHQ), described a similar system in an internal documen=
t in 1973.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, giv=
en the relatively expensive computers needed to implement it at the time, i=
t was considered to be mostly a curiosity and, as far as is publicly known,=
 was never deployed. His ideas and concepts were not revealed until 1997 du=
e to its top-secret classification.
</p><p>Kid-RSA (KRSA) is a simplified, insecure public-key cipher published=
 in 1997, designed for educational purposes. Kid-RSA gives insight into RSA=
 and other public-key ciphers, analogous to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Data_Encryption_Standard#Simplified_DES" title=3D"Data Encryption=
 Standard">simplified DES</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-23"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cr=
yptosystem#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-26=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Patent">Patent</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Patent"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patent" title=3D"Patent">pate=
nt</a> describing the RSA algorithm was granted to <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology" title=3D"Massachuse=
tts Institute of Technology">MIT</a> on 20 September 1983: <span><a rel=3D"=
nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://patents.google.com/patent=
/US4405829">U.S. patent 4,405,829</a></span> "Cryptographic communications =
system and method". From <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derwent_W=
orld_Patent_Index" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Derwent World Patent Inde=
x">DWPI</a>'s abstract of the patent:
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>The system includes a communications=
 channel coupled to at least one terminal having an encoding device and to =
at least one terminal having a decoding device. A message-to-be-transferred=
 is enciphered to ciphertext at the encoding terminal by encoding the messa=
ge as a number M in a predetermined set. That number is then raised to a fi=
rst predetermined power (associated with the intended receiver) and finally=
 computed. The remainder or residue, C, is... computed when the exponentiat=
ed number is divided by the product of two predetermined prime numbers (ass=
ociated with the intended receiver).</p></blockquote>
<p>A detailed description of the algorithm was published in August 1977, in=
 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_American" title=3D"=
Scientific American">Scientific American</a></i><span class=3D"nowrap" styl=
e=3D"padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/List_of_Martin_Gardner_Mathematical_Games_columns" title=3D"List of Marti=
n Gardner Mathematical Games columns">Mathematical Games</a> column.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Gardner1977_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-Gardner1977-2"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-SIAM_21-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-SIAM-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This preceded the=
 patent's filing date of December 1977. Consequently, the patent had no leg=
al standing outside the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Sta=
tes" title=3D"United States">United States</a>. Had Cocks' work been public=
ly known, a patent in the United States would not have been legal either.
</p><p>When the patent was issued, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Term_of_patent" title=3D"Term of patent">terms of patent</a> were 17 years=
. The patent was about to expire on 21 September 2000, but <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_Security" title=3D"RSA Security">RSA Security<=
/a> released the algorithm to the public domain on 6 September 2000.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Operation">Operation</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Operation"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The RSA algorithm involves four steps: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Key_(cryptography)" title=3D"Key (cryptography)">key</a> generation=
, key distribution, public-key operation (used for encryption or verifying =
a signature), and private key operation (used for decryption or signing a m=
essage).
</p><p>A basic principle behind RSA is the observation that it is practical=
 to find three very large positive integers <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">d</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">n</span>, such that for all integers <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> (<span class=3D"texhtml">0 =
=E2=89=A4 <i>x</i> &lt; <i>n</i></span>), both <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>=
x</i><sup><i>e</i></sup>)<sup><i>d</i></sup></span> and <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> have the same <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_division" title=3D"Euclidean division=
">remainder</a> when divided by <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">n</span> (they are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Modular_arithmetic#Congruence" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">congruent modul=
o</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>):<=
span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-m=
ath-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math dis=
play=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\di=
splaystyle (x^{e})^{d}\equiv x{\pmod {n}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
