quiv x{\pmod {n}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/eaa7b6f84d67707a138d1a45a8b148957f220831" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:21.383ex; height:3.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (=
x^{e})^{d}\equiv x{\pmod {n}}.}"></span>However, when given only <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> and <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>, it is infeasible to c=
ompute <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span><s=
up>th</sup> roots modulo <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">n</span>; that is, for uniform random <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span> (<span class=3D"texhtml">0 =E2=89=A4 =
<i>y</i> &lt; <i>n</i></span>), it is extremely difficult to find <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> such that <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i><sup><i>e</i></sup> =E2=89=A1 <i>y</i> (mod <i>n</=
i>)</span>.
</p><p>The integers <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">n</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e=
</span> form the public key and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">d</span> is the private key. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Modular_exponentiation" title=3D"Modular exponentiation">modu=
lar exponentiation</a> to the power of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> is used in encryption and in verifying sig=
natures, and exponentiation to the power of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> is used in decryption and in signing me=
ssages.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Key_generation">Key generat=
ion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryp=
tosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Key gene=
ration"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<p>The keys for the RSA algorithm are generated in the following way:
</p>
<ol><li>Choose two large <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_num=
ber" title=3D"Prime number">prime numbers</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">q</span>.
<ul><li>To make factoring infeasible, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">p</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">q</span> must be chosen at random from a large space of po=
ssibilities, such as all prime numbers between <span class=3D"texhtml">2<su=
p>1023</sup></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup>1024</sup></span> (co=
rresponding to a 2,048-bit key).  Many different algorithms for prime selec=
tion are used in practice.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-svenda2016mkq_29-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_n=
ote-svenda2016mkq-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span> and =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">q</span> are kept=
 secret.</li></ul></li>
<li>Compute <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =3D <i>pq</i></span>.
<ul><li><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> =
is used as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic"=
 title=3D"Modular arithmetic">modulus</a> for both the public and private k=
eys. Its length, usually expressed in bits, is the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Key_length" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Key length">key=
 length</a>.</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is r=
eleased as part of the public key.</li></ul></li>
<li>Compute <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</span>, where <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BB</span> is <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carmichael%27s_totient_function" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Carmichael's totient function">Carmichael's to=
tient function</a>. Since <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =3D <i>pq</i>, <=
i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>) =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_c=
ommon_multiple" title=3D"Least common multiple">lcm</a>(<i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>p<=
/i>),&nbsp;<i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>q</i>))</span>, and since <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">q</span> are prime, <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>p</i>) =3D <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
uler_totient_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Euler totient functio=
n">=CF=86</a></i>(<i>p</i>) =3D <i>p</i> =E2=88=92 1</span>, and likewise <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>q</i>) =3D <i>q</i> =E2=88=92 1</sp=
an>. Hence <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>) =3D lcm(<i>p</i>=
 =E2=88=92 1, <i>q</i> =E2=88=92 1)</span>.
<ul><li>The <span class=3D"texhtml">lcm</span> may be calculated through th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm" title=3D"Eu=
clidean algorithm">Euclidean algorithm</a>, since <span class=3D"texhtml">l=
cm(<i>a</i>,&nbsp;<i>b</i>) =3D <span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=
=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">|<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left=
:0.1em; padding-right:0.1em;"><i>ab</i></span>|</span><span class=3D"sr-onl=
y">/</span><span class=3D"den">gcd(<i>a</i>,&nbsp;<i>b</i>)</span></span>=
=E2=81=A0</span></span>.</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</span> is kept secret.<=
/li></ul></li>
<li>Choose an integer <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">e</span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml">1 &lt; <i>e</i> &lt; <i>=CE=
=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Greatest_common_divisor" title=3D"Greatest common diviso=
r">gcd</a>(<i>e</i>, <i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)) =3D 1</span>; that is, <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> and <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</span> are <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Coprime" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coprime">coprime</a>=
.
<ul><li><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> =
having a short <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bit-length" title=
=3D"Bit-length">bit-length</a> and small <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Hamming_weight" title=3D"Hamming weight">Hamming weight</a> results =
in more efficient encryption&nbsp;=E2=80=93  the most commonly chosen value=
 for <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> is =
<span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup>16</sup> + 1 =3D <span class=3D"nowrap"><span=
 data-sort-value=3D"7004655370000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>65<span style=3D"m=
argin-left:.25em;">537</span></span></span>. The smallest (and fastest) pos=
sible value for <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e=
</span> is 3, but such a small value for <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> may expose vulnerabilities in insecure pad=
ding schemes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Boneh99_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-Boneh99-30"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> is r=
eleased as part of the public key.</li></ul></li>
<li>Determine <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</=
span> as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>d</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>e</i><sup>=E2=88=921=
</sup> (mod <i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>))</span>; that is, <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_multiplicative_inverse" title=3D"Modular multipl=
icative inverse">modular multiplicative inverse</a> of <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> modulo <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</span>.
<ul><li>This means: solve for <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">d</span> the equation <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>de</i> =E2=89=
=A1 1 (mod <i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>))</span>; <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> can be computed efficiently by using th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_Euclidean_algorithm" ti=
tle=3D"Extended Euclidean algorithm">extended Euclidean algorithm</a>, sinc=
e, thanks to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</s=
pan> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</span> being copri=
me, said equation is a form of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%C=
3%A9zout%27s_identity" title=3D"B=C3=A9zout's identity">B=C3=A9zout's ident=
ity</a>, where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d<=
/span> is one of the coefficients.</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> is k=
ept secret as the <i>private key exponent</i>.</li></ul></li></ol>
<p>The <i>public key</i> consists of the modulus <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> and the public exponent <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span>. The <i>private ke=
y</i> consists of the private exponent <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span>, which must be kept secret. <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>, <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">q</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</span> must also be kept secret because they can be=
 used to calculate <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">d</span>. In fact, they can all be discarded after <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> has been computed.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RS=
A_cryptosystem#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"OriginalWithPhiN"></span>In the origina=
l RSA paper,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-rsa_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-rsa-3"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_totient_function" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Euler totient function">Euler totient function</a> <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i>(<i>n</i>) =3D (<i>p</i> =E2=88=92 1)(<i=
>q</i> =E2=88=92 1)</span> is used instead of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</span> for calculating the private exponent <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span>. Since <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i>(<i>n</i>)</span> is always divisible by <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</span>, the algorithm works as well=
. The possibility of using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_t=
otient_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Euler totient function">Eul=
er totient function</a> results also from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Lagrange%27s_theorem_(group_theory)" title=3D"Lagrange's theorem (g=
roup theory)">Lagrange's theorem</a> applied to the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplicative_group_of_integers_modulo_n" title=3D"Multi=
plicative group of integers modulo n">multiplicative group of integers modu=
lo <i>pq</i></a>. Thus any <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">d</span> satisfying <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>d</i>=E2=8B=85<i>e=
</i> =E2=89=A1 1 (mod <i>=CF=86</i>(<i>n</i>))</span> also satisfies <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>d</i>=E2=8B=85<i>e</i> =E2=89=A1 1 (mod <i>=CE=BB</i>(=
<i>n</i>))</span>. However, computing <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">d</span> modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i>(=
<i>n</i>)</span> will sometimes yield a result that is larger than necessar=
y (i.e. <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>d</i> &gt; <i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</span=
>). Most of the implementations of RSA will accept exponents generated usin=
g either method (if they use the private exponent <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> at all, rather than using the opt=
imized decryption method <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_crypt=
osystem#Using_the_Chinese_remainder_algorithm">based on the Chinese remaind=
er theorem</a> described below), but some standards such as <a rel=3D"nofol=
low" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/FIPS=
/NIST.FIPS.186-4.pdf#page=3D63">FIPS&nbsp;186-4</a> (Section B.3.1) may req=
uire that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>d</i> &lt; <i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</sp=
an>. Any "oversized" private exponents not meeting this criterion may alway=
s be reduced modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>)</span> =
to obtain a smaller equivalent exponent.
</p><p>Note: The authors of the original RSA paper carry out the key genera=
tion by choosing <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
d</span> and then computing <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">e</span> as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular=
_multiplicative_inverse" title=3D"Modular multiplicative inverse">modular m=
ultiplicative inverse</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">d</span> modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i>(<i>n</i>)=
</span>, whereas most current implementations of RSA, such as those followi=
ng <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PKCS1" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"PKCS1">PKCS#1</a>, do the reverse=E2=80=94choose <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> and compute <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> from it. Since <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> can safely be sm=
all and fixed, whereas <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">d</span> must be chosen from a large enough space to resist attack, t=
he modern approach can reduce the cost of the public-key operation without =
loss of security.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-rsa_3-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-rsa-3"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-pkcs1_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-pkcs1-33"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Key_distribution">Key distr=
ibution</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_=
cryptosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Key =
distribution"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>Suppose that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_and_Bob" tit=
le=3D"Alice and Bob">Bob</a> wants to send secret messages to <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_and_Bob" title=3D"Alice and Bob">Alice</a=
>, or verify messages from Alice. If they decide to use RSA, Bob must know =
Alice's public key to encrypt his secret messages or verify Alice's message=
s, and Alice must use her private key to decrypt Bob's secret messages or s=
ign her own messages.
</p><p>To enable Bob to send his encrypted messages or verify her future me=
ssages, Alice transmits her public key <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>n</i>, <=
i>e</i>)</span> to Bob via a reliable, but not necessarily secret, route. A=
lice's private key <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>d</i>)</span> is never distr=
ibuted.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Encryption">Encryption</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Encryption"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>After Bob obtains Alice's public key, he can send a message <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">M</span> to Alice.
</p><p>To do it, he first turns <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">M</span> into an integer <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Padding_(cryptography)" title=3D"Padding (cryptography)">padded</a> pla=
intext, such that <span class=3D"texhtml">0 =E2=89=A4 <i>m</i> &lt; <i>n</i=
></span>, by using an agreed-upon reversible protocol known as a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#Padding_schemes">padding sc=
heme</a>. He then computes the ciphertext <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>, using Alice's public key <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span>, by:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle c\equiv m^{e}{\pmod {n}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>c</mi>
        <mo>=E2=89=A1<!-- =E2=89=A1 --></mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>m</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>e</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mspace width=3D"1em"></mspace>
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
          <mi>mod</mi>
          <mspace width=3D"0.333em"></mspace>
          <mi>n</mi>
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle c\equiv m^{e}=
{\pmod {n}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/2e52f73642221fad08a441c70d514ae06600cc4b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:18.87ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle c\=
equiv m^{e}{\pmod {n}}.}"></span>
</p><p>This can be done reasonably quickly, even for very large numbers, us=
ing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_exponentiation" title=
=3D"Modular exponentiation">modular exponentiation</a>. Bob then transmits =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> to Alice=
. Note that at least nine values of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">m</span> will yield a ciphertext <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> equal to
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span>,<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but this is very unlikely to o=
ccur in practice.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Decryption">Decryption</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Decryption"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>Alice can recover <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">m</span> from <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>c</span> by using her private key exponent <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> by computing
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle c^{d}\equiv (m^{e})^{d}\equiv m{\pmod {n}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mi>c</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>d</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=E2=89=A1<!-- =E2=89=A1 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>m</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>e</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <msup>
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>d</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=E2=89=A1<!-- =E2=89=A1 --></mo>
        <mi>m</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mspace width=3D"1em"></mspace>
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
          <mi>mod</mi>
          <mspace width=3D"0.333em"></mspace>
          <mi>n</mi>
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle c^{d}\equiv (=
m^{e})^{d}\equiv m{\pmod {n}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/111a80bbccad42f94fe247a2b3cc68664e682744" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:28.002ex; height:3.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle c=
^{d}\equiv (m^{e})^{d}\equiv m{\pmod {n}}.}"></span>
</p><p>Given <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</s=
pan>, she can recover the original message <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">M</span> by reversing the padding scheme, or disc=
ard it as corrupted if the padding is invalid.
</p><p>Alice <b>must</b> discard <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">m</span> if the padding is invalid: if she reveals any info=
rmation about <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</=
span> when it has invalid padding, an adversary could exploit this to decry=
pt (or sign) messages without knowing the private key, by sending her rando=
m or maliciously crafted ciphertexts and observing how she responds.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Bleichenbacher1998_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-Bleichenbacher1998-35"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Example">Example</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;a=
