</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/b1d66fbfbbdea9bb287238fa364c3445201b511f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:55.552ex; height:3.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle m=
^{ed}=3Dm^{1+h\varphi (n)}=3Dm(m^{\varphi (n)})^{h}\equiv m(1)^{h}\equiv m{=
\pmod {n}},}"></span>
</p><p>where the second-last congruence follows from <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler%27s_theorem" title=3D"Euler's theorem">Euler's the=
orem</a>.
</p><p>More generally, for any <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">e</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">d</span> satisfying <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ed</i> =E2=89=A1 1=
 (mod <i>=CE=BB</i>(<i>n</i>))</span>, the same conclusion follows from <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carmichael_function#Carmichael's_theo=
rem" title=3D"Carmichael function">Carmichael's generalization of Euler's t=
heorem</a>, which states that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i><sup><i>=CE=
=BB</i>(n)</sup> =E2=89=A1 1 (mod <i>n</i>)</span> for all <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> relatively prime to <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>.
</p><p>When <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</sp=
an> is not relatively prime to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">n</span>, the argument just given is invalid. This is highly =
improbable (only a proportion of <span class=3D"texhtml">1/<i>p</i> + 1/<i>=
q</i> =E2=88=92 1/(<i>pq</i>)</span> numbers have this property), but even =
in this case, the desired congruence is still true. Either <span class=3D"t=
exhtml"><i>m</i> =E2=89=A1 0 (mod <i>p</i>)</span> or <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>m</i> =E2=89=A1 0 (mod <i>q</i>)</span>, and these cases can be treat=
ed using the previous proof.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Padding">Padding</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Padding"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Attacks_against_plain_RSA">=
Attacks against plain RSA</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D=
"Edit section: Attacks against plain RSA"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There are a number of attacks against plain RSA as described below.
</p>
<ul><li>When encrypting with low encryption exponents (e.g., <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>e</i> =3D 3</span>) and small values of the <span class=3D"tex=
html mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> (i.e., <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>m</i> &lt; <i>n</i><sup>1/<i>e</i></sup></span>), the result of <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i><sup><i>e</i></sup></span> is strictly less th=
an the modulus <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n<=
/span>. In this case, ciphertexts can be decrypted easily by taking the <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span>th root of t=
he ciphertext over the integers.</li>
<li>If the same clear-text message is sent to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> or more recipients in an encrypted wa=
y, and the receivers share the same exponent <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span>, but different <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">q</span>, and therefore <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>, then it is easy to decrypt the=
 original clear-text message via the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Chinese_remainder_theorem" title=3D"Chinese remainder theorem">Chinese r=
emainder theorem</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johan_H%C3%A=
5stad" title=3D"Johan H=C3=A5stad">Johan H=C3=A5stad</a> noticed that this =
attack is possible even if the clear texts are not equal, but the attacker =
knows a linear relation between them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-4=
4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> This attack was later improved by <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Don_Coppersmith" title=3D"Don Coppersmith">Don Coppersmith</=
a> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coppersmith%27s_attack" ti=
tle=3D"Coppersmith's attack">Coppersmith's attack</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_crypto=
system#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Because RSA encryption is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De=
terministic_algorithm" title=3D"Deterministic algorithm">deterministic encr=
yption algorithm</a> (i.e., has no random component) an attacker can succes=
sfully launch a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chosen_plaintext_a=
ttack" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chosen plaintext attack">chosen plain=
text attack</a> against the cryptosystem, by encrypting likely plaintexts u=
nder the public key and test whether they are equal to the ciphertext. A cr=
yptosystem is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semantically_=
secure" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Semantically secure">semantically se=
cure</a> if an attacker cannot distinguish two encryptions from each other,=
 even if the attacker knows (or has chosen) the corresponding plaintexts. R=
SA without padding is not semantically secure.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#ci=
te_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>RSA has the property that the product of two ciphertexts is equal to th=
e encryption of the product of the respective plaintexts. That is, <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i><sub>1</sub><sup><i>e</i></sup><i>m</i><sub>2</sub>=
<sup><i>e</i></sup> =E2=89=A1 (<i>m</i><sub>1</sub><i>m</i><sub>2</sub>)<su=
p><i>e</i></sup> (mod <i>n</i>)</span>. Because of this multiplicative prop=
erty, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chosen-ciphertext_attack" =
title=3D"Chosen-ciphertext attack">chosen-ciphertext attack</a> is possible=
. E.g., an attacker who wants to know the decryption of a ciphertext <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>m</i><sup><i>e</i></sup> (mod <i>n<=
/i>)</span> may ask the holder of the private key <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> to decrypt an unsuspicious-lookin=
g ciphertext <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i>=E2=80=B2 =E2=89=A1 <i>cr</i><=
sup><i>e</i></sup> (mod <i>n</i>)</span> for some value <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> chosen by the attacker. Bec=
ause of the multiplicative property, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">c</span>' is the encryption of <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>mr</i> (mod <i>n</i>)</span>. Hence, if the attacker is successful with =
the attack, they will learn <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>mr</i> (mod <i>n</i>=
),</span> from which they can derive the message <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> by multiplying <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>mr</i></span> with the modular inverse of <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> modulo <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bleichenbacher=
1998_35-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA=
_cryptosystem#cite_note-Bleichenbacher1998-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-Davida1982_47-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-Davida1982-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Given the private exponent <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">d</span>, one can efficiently factor the modulus <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =3D <i>pq</i></span>. And given factorization of the =
modulus <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =3D <i>pq</i></span>, one can obta=
in any private key (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">d</span>',&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">n</span>) generated against a public key (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span>',&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Boneh99_30-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#ci=
te_note-Boneh99-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Padding_schemes">Padding sc=
hemes</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cr=
yptosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Paddi=
ng schemes"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>To avoid these problems, practical RSA implementations typically embed s=
ome form of structured, randomized <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Padding_(cryptography)" title=3D"Padding (cryptography)">padding</a> into =
the value <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span=
> before encrypting it. This padding ensures that <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> does not fall into the range of i=
nsecure plaintexts, and that a given message, once padded, will encrypt to =
one of a large number of different possible ciphertexts.
</p><p>Standards such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PKCS1" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"PKCS1">PKCS#1</a> have been carefully designed=
 to securely pad messages prior to RSA encryption. Because these schemes pa=
d the plaintext <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m=
</span> with some number of additional bits, the size of the un-padded mess=
age <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">M</span> must=
 be somewhat smaller. RSA padding schemes must be carefully designed so as =
to prevent sophisticated attacks that may be facilitated by a predictable m=
essage structure. Early versions of the PKCS#1 standard (up to version 1.5)=
 used a construction that appears to make RSA semantically secure. However,=
 at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Cryptology_Confe=
rence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International Cryptology Conference">=
Crypto</a> 1998, Bleichenbacher showed that this version is vulnerable to a=
 practical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adaptive_chosen-ciphert=
ext_attack" title=3D"Adaptive chosen-ciphertext attack">adaptive chosen-cip=
hertext attack</a>. Furthermore, at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Eurocrypt" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eurocrypt">Eurocrypt</a> 2000, =
Coron et al.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> showed tha=
t for some types of messages, this padding does not provide a high enough l=
evel of security. Later versions of the standard include <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optimal_Asymmetric_Encryption_Padding" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Optimal Asymmetric Encryption Padding">Optimal Asymmetric=
 Encryption Padding</a> (OAEP), which prevents these attacks. As such, OAEP=
 should be used in any new application, and PKCS#1&nbsp;v1.5 padding should=
 be replaced wherever possible. The PKCS#1 standard also incorporates proce=
ssing schemes designed to provide additional security for RSA signatures, e=
.g. the Probabilistic Signature Scheme for RSA (<a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/RSA-PSS" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"RSA-PSS">RSA-PSS</a>)=
.
</p><p>Secure padding schemes such as RSA-PSS are as essential for the secu=
rity of message signing as they are for message encryption. Two USA patents=
 on PSS were granted (<span><a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" hre=
f=3D"https://patents.google.com/patent/US6266771">U.S. patent 6,266,771</a>=
</span> and <span><a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https=
://patents.google.com/patent/US7036014">U.S. patent 7,036,014</a></span>); =
however, these patents expired on 24 July 2009 and 25 April 2010 respective=
ly. Use of PSS no longer seems to be encumbered by patents.<sup class=3D"no=
print Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research" title=3D"Wikipedia:N=
o original research"><span title=3D"The material near this tag possibly con=
tains original research. (August 2019)">original research?</span></a></i>]<=
/sup> Note that using different RSA key pairs for encryption and signing is=
 potentially more secure.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-49"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Security_and_practical_cons=
iderations">Security and practical considerations</h2><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&am=
p;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Security and practical consideration=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Using_the_Chinese_remainder=
_algorithm">Using the Chinese remainder algorithm</h3><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&am=
p;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Using the Chinese remainder algorith=
m"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<p>For efficiency, many popular crypto libraries (such as <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenSSL" title=3D"OpenSSL">OpenSSL</a>, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_(programming_language)" title=3D"Java (p=
rogramming language)">Java</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/.NET_Framework" title=3D".NET Framework">.NET</a>) use for decryption and =
signing the following optimization based on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem" title=3D"Chinese remainder theorem=
">Chinese remainder theorem</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-50"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"whit=
e-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Cit=
ation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim=
 needs references to reliable sources. (December 2023)">citation needed</sp=
an></a></i>]</sup> The following values are precomputed and stored as part =
of the private key:
