</p><p>This is more efficient than computing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Exponentiation_by_squaring" title=3D"Exponentiation by squaring"=
>exponentiation by squaring</a>, even though two modular exponentiations ha=
ve to be computed. The reason is that these two modular exponentiations bot=
h use a smaller exponent and a smaller modulus.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Integer_factorization_and_t=
he_RSA_problem">Integer factorization and the RSA problem</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Integer factorization and=
 the RSA problem"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_Factoring_Challenge"=
 title=3D"RSA Factoring Challenge">RSA Factoring Challenge</a>, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_factorization_records" title=3D"Integ=
er factorization records">Integer factorization records</a>, and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shor%27s_algorithm" title=3D"Shor's algorith=
m">Shor's algorithm</a></div>
<p>The security of the RSA cryptosystem is based on two mathematical proble=
ms: the problem of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_factori=
zation" title=3D"Integer factorization">factoring large numbers</a> and the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_problem" title=3D"RSA problem=
">RSA problem</a>. Full decryption of an RSA ciphertext is thought to be in=
feasible on the assumption that both of these problems are <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_hardness_assumption" title=3D"Comput=
ational hardness assumption">hard</a>, i.e., no efficient algorithm exists =
for solving them. Providing security against <i>partial</i> decryption may =
require the addition of a secure <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
adding_(cryptography)" title=3D"Padding (cryptography)">padding scheme</a>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_problem" title=3D"R=
SA problem">RSA problem</a> is defined as the task of taking <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span>th roots modulo a compo=
site <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>: re=
covering a value <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
m</span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>m</i><sup>=
<i>e</i></sup> (mod <i>n</i>)</span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>n</=
i>, <i>e</i>)</span> is an RSA public key, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> is an RSA ciphertext. Currently the =
most promising approach to solving the RSA problem is to factor the modulus=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>. With t=
he ability to recover prime factors, an attacker can compute the secret exp=
onent <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> fr=
om a public key <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>n</i>, <i>e</i>)</span>, then d=
ecrypt <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> u=
sing the standard procedure. To accomplish this, an attacker factors <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> into <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">q</span>, and computes <span=
 class=3D"texhtml">lcm(<i>p</i> =E2=88=92 1, <i>q</i> =E2=88=92 1)</span> t=
hat allows the determination of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">d</span> from <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">e</span>. No polynomial-time method for factoring large integer=
s on a classical computer has yet been found, but it has not been proven th=
at none exists; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_factor=
ization" title=3D"Integer factorization">integer factorization</a> for a di=
scussion of this problem.
</p><p>The first RSA-512 factorization in 1999 used hundreds of computers a=
nd required the equivalent of 8,400 MIPS years, over an elapsed time of abo=
ut seven months.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-53"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By 200=
9, Benjamin Moody could factor an 512-bit RSA key in 73 days using only pub=
lic software (GGNFS) and his desktop computer (a dual-core <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Athlon64" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Athlon64"=
>Athlon64</a> with a 1,900&nbsp;MHz CPU). Just less than 5&nbsp;gigabytes o=
f disk storage was required and about 2.5&nbsp;gigabytes of RAM for the sie=
ving process.
</p><p>Rivest, Shamir, and Adleman noted<sup id=3D"cite_ref-rsa_3-3" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#ci=
te_note-rsa-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> that Miller has shown that =E2=80=93 assuming the=
 truth of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_Riemann_=
hypothesis" title=3D"Generalized Riemann hypothesis">extended Riemann hypot=
hesis</a> =E2=80=93 finding <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">d</span> from <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">n</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">e</span> is as hard as factoring <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">n</span> into <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">p</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">q</span> (up to a polynomial time difference).<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cr=
yptosystem#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, Rivest, Shamir, and Adleman n=
oted, in section IX/D of their paper, that they had not found a proof that =
inverting RSA is as hard as factoring.
</p><p>As of 2020<sup class=3D"plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update=
" style=3D"display:none;"><a class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;action=3Dedit">[update]=
</a></sup>, the largest publicly known factored <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/RSA_number" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"RSA number">RSA nu=
mber</a> had 829&nbsp;bits (250 decimal digits, <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/RSA-250" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"RSA-250">RSA-250</a>)=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Its factorization, by=
 a state-of-the-art distributed implementation, took about 2,700 CPU-years.=
 In practice, RSA keys are typically 1024 to 4096 bits long. In 2003, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_Security" title=3D"RSA Security">RS=
A Security</a> estimated that 1024-bit keys were likely to become crackable=
 by 2010.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-twirl_56-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-twirl-56"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 As of 2020, it is not known whether such keys can be cracked, but minimum =
recommendations have moved to at least 2048&nbsp;bits.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-k=
eymanagement_57-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-keymanagement-57"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is general=
ly presumed that RSA is secure if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">n</span> is sufficiently large, outside of quantum computi=
ng.
</p><p>If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span=
> is 300&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bit" title=3D"Bit">b=
its</a> or shorter, it can be factored in a few hours on a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Personal_computer" title=3D"Personal computer">per=
sonal computer</a>, using software already freely available. Keys of 512&nb=
sp;bits have been shown to be practically breakable in 1999, when <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA-155" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"R=
SA-155">RSA-155</a> was factored by using several hundred computers, and th=
ese are now factored in a few weeks using common hardware. Exploits using 5=
12-bit code-signing certificates that may have been factored were reported =
in 2011.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A theoretical =
hardware device named <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TWIRL" title=
=3D"TWIRL">TWIRL</a>, described by Shamir and Tromer in 2003, called into q=
uestion the security of 1024-bit keys.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-twirl_56-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#ci=
te_note-twirl-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1994, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Shor" title=
=3D"Peter Shor">Peter Shor</a> showed that a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Quantum_computer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quantum compute=
r">quantum computer</a> =E2=80=93 if one could ever be practically created =
for the purpose =E2=80=93 would be able to factor in <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_time" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polynomi=
al time">polynomial time</a>, breaking RSA; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Shor%27s_algorithm" title=3D"Shor's algorithm">Shor's algorit=
hm</a>.
</p>
