<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coppersmith%27s_attack" =
title=3D"Coppersmith's attack">Coppersmith's attack</a> and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiener%27s_attack" title=3D"Wiener's attack">Wien=
er's attack</a></div>
<p>Finding the large primes <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">p</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">q</span> is usually done by testing random numbers of the correct si=
ze with probabilistic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primality_te=
st" title=3D"Primality test">primality tests</a> that quickly eliminate vir=
tually all of the nonprimes.
</p><p>The numbers <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">p</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">q<=
/span> should not be "too close", lest the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Fermat_factorization" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fermat factor=
ization">Fermat factorization</a> for <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">n</span> be successful. If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
p</i> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i></span> is less than <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>n<=
/i><sup>1/4</sup></span> (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =3D <i>p</i>=E2=
=8B=85<i>q</i></span>, which even for "small" 1024-bit values of <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is <span class=3D"=
nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7077300000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>3<spa=
n style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>77<=
/sup></span>), solving for <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">p</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">q</span> is trivial. Furthermore, if either <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>p</i> =E2=88=92 1</span> or <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i> =E2=88=92 1<=
/span> has only small prime factors, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">n</span> can be factored quickly by <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pollard%27s_p_%E2%88%92_1_algorithm" title=3D"Pollard=
's p =E2=88=92 1 algorithm">Pollard's <i>p</i> =E2=88=92 1 algorithm</a>, a=
nd hence such values of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">p</span> or <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">q</span> should be discarded.
</p><p>It is important that the private exponent <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> be large enough. Michael J.&nbsp;W=
iener showed that if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">p</span> is between <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">q</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>q</i></span> (which is quit=
e typical) and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>d</i> &lt; <i>n</i><sup>1/4</sup>=
/3</span>, then <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d=
</span> can be computed efficiently from <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> and&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-wiener_59-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_=
note-wiener-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>There is no known attack against small public exponents such as <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i> =3D 3</span>, provided that the proper padding=
 is used. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coppersmith%27s_attack" =
title=3D"Coppersmith's attack">Coppersmith's attack</a> has many applicatio=
ns in attacking RSA specifically if the public exponent <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> is small and if the encrypt=
ed message is short and not padded. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/65537" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"65537">65537</a> is a commonly used=
 value for&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e=
</span>; this value can be regarded as a compromise between avoiding potent=
ial small-exponent attacks and still allowing efficient encryptions (or sig=
nature verification). The NIST Special Publication on Computer Security (SP=
&nbsp;800-78 Rev.&nbsp;1 of August 2007) does not allow public exponents <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> smaller th=
an 65537, but does not state a reason for this restriction.
</p><p>In October 2017, a team of researchers from <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Masaryk_University" title=3D"Masaryk University">Masaryk U=
niversity</a> announced the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ROCA_v=
ulnerability" title=3D"ROCA vulnerability">ROCA vulnerability</a>, which af=
fects RSA keys generated by an algorithm embodied in a library from <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infineon" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Infineon">Infineon</a> known as RSALib. A large number of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smart_card" title=3D"Smart card">smart cards</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trusted_platform_module" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Trusted platform module">trusted platform modules=
</a> (TPM) were shown to be affected. Vulnerable RSA keys are easily identi=
fied using a test program the team released.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-nemecsys_60=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_crypto=
system#cite_note-nemecsys-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Importance_of_strong_random=
_number_generation">Importance of strong random number generation</h3><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: Importance of strong=
 random number generation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A cryptographically strong <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rand=
om_number_generator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Random number generator=
">random number generator</a>, which has been properly seeded with adequate=
 entropy, must be used to generate the primes <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">q</span>. An analysis comparing millions of public=
 keys gathered from the Internet was carried out in early 2012 by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arjen_Klaas_Lenstra" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Arjen Klaas Lenstra">Arjen K.&nbsp;Lenstra</a>, James P.&nbsp;Hu=
ghes, Maxime Augier, Joppe W.&nbsp;Bos, Thorsten Kleinjung and Christophe W=
achter. They were able to factor 0.2% of the keys using only Euclid's algor=
ithm.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryp=
tosystem#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" =
style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Wikipedia:Verifiability#Self-published_sources" title=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiab=
ility"><span title=3D"The material near this tag may rely on a self-publish=
ed source. (December 2023)">self-published source?</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>They exploited a weakness unique to cryptosystems based on integer f=
actorization. If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =3D <i>pq</i></span> is o=
ne public key, and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i>=E2=80=B2 =3D <i>p</i>=
=E2=80=B2<i>q</i>=E2=80=B2</span> is another, then if by chance <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i> =3D <i>p</i>=E2=80=B2</span> (but <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">q</span> is not equal to <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">q</span>'), then a simple co=
mputation of <span class=3D"texhtml">gcd(<i>n</i>, <i>n</i>=E2=80=B2) =3D <=
i>p</i></span> factors both <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">n</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">n</span>', totally compromising both keys. Lenstra et al. note that =
this problem can be minimized by using a strong random seed of bit length t=
wice the intended security level, or by employing a deterministic function =
to choose <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">q</span=
> given <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>,=
 instead of choosing <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">p</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
q</span> independently.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nadia_Heninger" title=3D"Na=
dia Heninger">Nadia Heninger</a> was part of a group that did a similar exp=
eriment. They used an idea of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dani=
el_J._Bernstein" title=3D"Daniel J. Bernstein">Daniel J.&nbsp;Bernstein</a>=
 to compute the GCD of each RSA key <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">n</span> against the product of all the other keys <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>' they had fou=
nd (a 729-million-digit number), instead of computing each <span class=3D"t=
exhtml">gcd(<i>n</i>, <i>n</i>=E2=80=B2)</span> separately, thereby achievi=
ng a very significant speedup, since after one large division, the GCD prob=
lem is of normal size.
</p><p>Heninger says in her blog that the bad keys occurred almost entirely=
 in embedded applications, including "firewalls, routers, VPN devices, remo=
te server administration devices, printers, projectors, and VOIP phones" fr=
om more than 30 manufacturers. Heninger explains that the one-shared-prime =
problem uncovered by the two groups results from situations where the pseud=
orandom number generator is poorly seeded initially, and then is reseeded b=
etween the generation of the first and second primes. Using seeds of suffic=
iently high entropy obtained from key stroke timings or electronic diode no=
ise or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_noise" title=3D=
"Atmospheric noise">atmospheric noise</a> from a radio receiver tuned betwe=
en stations should solve the problem.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-6=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>Strong random number generation is important throughout every phase =
of public-key cryptography. For instance, if a weak generator is used for t=
he symmetric keys that are being distributed by RSA, then an eavesdropper c=
ould bypass RSA and guess the symmetric keys directly.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Timing_attacks">Timing atta=
cks</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryp=
tosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Timing =
attacks"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Carl_Kocher" title=3D"Paul=
 Carl Kocher">Kocher</a> described a new attack on RSA in 1995: if the atta=
cker Eve knows Alice's hardware in sufficient detail and is able to measure=
 the decryption times for several known ciphertexts, Eve can deduce the dec=
ryption key <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</sp=
an> quickly. This attack can also be applied against the RSA signature sche=
me. In 2003, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dan_Boneh" title=3D"D=
an Boneh">Boneh</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Brum=
ley" title=3D"David Brumley">Brumley</a> demonstrated a more practical atta=
ck capable of recovering RSA factorizations over a network connection (e.g.=
, from a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Sockets_Layer" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Secure Sockets Layer">Secure Sockets Layer</a> =
(SSL)-enabled webserver).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Boneh03_64-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-Bon=
eh03-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> This attack takes advantage of information leaked by t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem" titl=
e=3D"Chinese remainder theorem">Chinese remainder theorem</a> optimization =
used by many RSA implementations.
</p><p>One way to thwart these attacks is to ensure that the decryption ope=
ration takes a constant amount of time for every ciphertext. However, this =
approach can significantly reduce performance. Instead, most RSA implementa=
tions use an alternate technique known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Blinding_(cryptography)" title=3D"Blinding (cryptography)">cryptogr=
aphic blinding</a>. RSA blinding makes use of the multiplicative property o=
f RSA. Instead of computing <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i><sup><i>d</i></=
sup> (mod <i>n</i>)</span>, Alice first chooses a secret random value <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> and computes =
<span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>r</i><sup><i>e</i></sup><i>c</i>)<sup><i>d</i><=
/sup> (mod <i>n</i>)</span>. The result of this computation, after applying=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler%27s_theorem" title=3D"Euler=
's theorem">Euler's theorem</a>, is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>rc</i><sup><=
i>d</i></sup> (mod <i>n</i>)</span>, and so the effect of <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> can be removed by multipl=
ying by its inverse. A new value of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">r</span> is chosen for each ciphertext. With blinding ap=
plied, the decryption time is no longer correlated to the value of the inpu=
t ciphertext, and so the timing attack fails.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Adaptive_chosen-ciphertext_=
attacks">Adaptive chosen-ciphertext attacks</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Adaptive chosen-ciphertext attacks"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In 1998, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_Bleichenbacher"=
 title=3D"Daniel Bleichenbacher">Daniel Bleichenbacher</a> described the fi=
rst practical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adaptive_chosen-ciph=
ertext_attack" title=3D"Adaptive chosen-ciphertext attack">adaptive chosen-=
ciphertext attack</a> against RSA-encrypted messages using the PKCS&nbsp;#1=
&nbsp;v1 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padding_(cryptography)" t=
itle=3D"Padding (cryptography)">padding scheme</a> (a padding scheme random=
izes and adds structure to an RSA-encrypted message, so it is possible to d=
etermine whether a decrypted message is valid). Due to flaws with the PKCS&=
nbsp;#1 scheme, Bleichenbacher was able to mount a practical attack against=
 RSA implementations of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure=
_Sockets_Layer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Secure Sockets Layer">Secure=
 Sockets Layer</a> protocol and to recover session keys. As a result of thi=
s work, cryptographers now recommend the use of provably secure padding sch=
emes such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optimal_Asymmetric_En=
cryption_Padding" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Optimal Asymmetric Encrypt=
ion Padding">Optimal Asymmetric Encryption Padding</a>, and RSA Laboratorie=
s has released new versions of PKCS&nbsp;#1 that are not vulnerable to thes=
e attacks.
</p><p>A variant of this attack, dubbed "BERserk", came back in 2014.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-65" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#ci=
te_note-66"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> It impacted the Mozilla NSS Crypto Library, which w=
as used notably by Firefox and Chrome.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Side-channel_analysis_attac=
ks">Side-channel analysis attacks</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" =
title=3D"Edit section: Side-channel analysis attacks"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A side-channel attack using branch-prediction analysis (BPA) has been de=
scribed. Many processors use a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bra=
nch_predictor" title=3D"Branch predictor">branch predictor</a> to determine=
 whether a conditional branch in the instruction flow of a program is likel=
y to be taken or not. Often these processors also implement <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simultaneous_multithreading" title=3D"Simultaneou=
s multithreading">simultaneous multithreading</a> (SMT). Branch-prediction =
analysis attacks use a spy process to discover (statistically) the private =
key when processed with these processors.
</p><p>Simple Branch Prediction Analysis (SBPA) claims to improve BPA in a =
non-statistical way. In their paper, "On the Power of Simple Branch Predict=
ion Analysis",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the auth=
ors of SBPA (Onur Aciicmez and Cetin Kaya Koc) claim to have discovered 508=
 out of 512&nbsp;bits of an RSA key in 10 iterations.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fault_injection_attack">Fau=
lt injection attack</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit =
section: Fault injection attack"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A power-fault attack on RSA implementations was described in 2010 <sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-68" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>The author recovered the key =
by varying the CPU power voltage outside limits; this caused multiple power=
 faults on the server.
</p><p>The CRT implementation is sensitive to <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Fault_injection" title=3D"Fault injection">fault injection</a> =
attacks. If an attacker can obtain 1 faulty signature, the private key can =
be calculated.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-69"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Tricky_implementation">Tric=
ky implementation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DRSA_cryptosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Tricky implementation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There are many details to keep in mind in order to implement RSA securel=
y (strong <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_number_gene=
rator" title=3D"Pseudorandom number generator">PRNG</a>, acceptable public =
exponent, etc.). This makes the implementation challenging, to the point th=
at the book <i>Practical Cryptography With Go</i> suggests avoiding RSA if =
possible.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-70" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem#cite_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Implementations">Implementa=
tions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRSA_cr=
yptosystem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Imple=
mentations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>Some cryptography libraries that provide support for RSA include:
</p>
